04737nam a22007935i 9780814745403DE-B159720220329044247.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220329t19991999nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808147454037 a10.18574/nyu/97808147454032doi  a(DE-B1597)547562  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aKF9218 .R634 2001 7aLAW0530002bisacsh04a345.731 aRobinson, Paul H., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWould You Convict? :bSeventeen Cases That Challenged the Law /cPaul H. Robinson. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[1999] 4c©1999  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tPrologue -- t1 Punishing Intent, Harm, or Dangerousness? -- t2 Knowing the Law’s Commands -- t3 Can Committing a Crime Be Doing the Right Thing? -- t4 Can Doing the Wrong Thing Ever Be Blameless? -- t5 Martyrs for Our Safety -- tEpilogue -- tAppendix -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA police trooper inspects a car during a routine traffic stop and finds a vast cache of weapons, complete with automatic rifles, thousands of rounds of ammunition, and black ski masks-a veritable bank robber's kit. Should the men in the car be charged? If so, with what? A son neglects to care for his elderly mother, whose emaciated form is discovered shortly before she dies a painful death. Is the son's neglect punishable, and if so how? A career con man writes one bad check too many and is sentenced to life in prison-for a check in the amount of $129.75. Is this just? A thief steals a backpack, only to find it contains a terrorist bomb. He alerts the police and saves lives, transforming himself from petty criminal to national hero. These are just a few of the many provocative cases that Paul Robinson presents and unravels in Would You Convict? Judging crimes and meting out punishment has long been an informal national pasttime. High-profile crimes or particularly brutal ones invariably prompt endless debate, in newspapers, on television, in coffee shops, and on front porches. Our very nature inclines us to be armchair judges, freely waving our metaphorical gavels and opining as to the innocence or guilt-and suitable punishment-of alleged criminals. Confronting this impulse, Paul Robinson here presents a series of unusual episodes that not only challenged the law, but that defy a facile or knee-jerk verdict. Narrating the facts in compelling, but detached detail, Robinson invites readers to sentence the transgressor (or not), before revealing the final outcome of the case. The cases described in Would You Convict? engage, shock, even repel. Without a doubt, they will challenge you and your belief system. And the way in which juries and judges have resolved them will almost certainly surprise you.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 0aCriminal lawzUnited States. 0aTrialszUnited States. 7aLAW / Jury.2bisacsh  aaccount.  abox.  acases.  adirectly.  aengaging.  ajurors.  aplaces.  areader.  athat.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000z978311071692440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814745403423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814745403/original  a978-3-11-071692-4  New York University Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK